{"title_page": "Parry Liyanage", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Parry Liyanage\n|birth_date=  \n|death_date=  \n|birth_place= \n|death_place=\n|placeofburial= \n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears=             \n|rank=[[Brigadier]]\n|branch= [[Sri Lanka Army]]\n|commands=Quartermaster-General,<br>Adjutant General \n|unit=[[Sri Lanka Artillery]]\n|battles=[[Sri Lankan Civil War]],<br /> [[1987-89 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|Insurrection 1987-89]]\n|awards=\n|laterwork=  \n}}\n[[Brigadier]] '''Rohan Parakrama \"Parry\" Liyanage''' was a [[Sri Lanka]]n military officer, athlete  and coach, who was the former [[Quartermaster general#Sri Lanka|Quartermaster-General]] and [[Adjutant General#Sri Lanka|Adjutant General]] of the [[Sri Lanka Army]]. He was the National record holder for [[shot put]], senior vice president of the Athletic Association of Sri Lanka and National Athletic Coach.<ref>[http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/06/16/spo06.asp Brig. Parry no more] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019105456/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/06/16/spo06.asp |date=2012-10-19 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nEducated at [[Royal College, Colombo]], he joined the army in the first batch of officers to be trained locally at the Officer Cadets\u2019 School of the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy|Army Training Center]] on 27 April 1968 and was commissioned into the [[Ceylon Artillery]] as a [[Second Lieutenant]].  \n\n== Embilipitiya Schoolboys' Affair==\nAt the height of the [[1987\u20131989 JVP insurrection]], Dayananda Lokugalapaththi, the Principal of Embilipitiya Maha Vidyalaya, got angry at several school boys for mocking the love affairs of his son with another student. Lokugalapaththi had been accused to have had the Army take the school boys to Sevana army camp where they were killed. Colonel Liyanage was the district coordination officer of the area and had been friendly with Lokugalapaththi.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hoole |first1=Rajan |title=Embilipitiya Schoolboys\u2019 Affair \u2013 The Thin End Of The Wedge |url=https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/embilipitiya-schoolboys-affair-the-thin-end-of-the-wedge/ |website=Colombo Telegraph |publisher=Colombo Telegraph |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> The boys were forced to write suicide notes prior to death, forced to eat broken glass and nails, and subsequently buried in the [[Sooriyakanda mass grave]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Akmeemana |first1=Gamini |title=Sooriyakanda: ghosts, scapegoats and real killers |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/110628/Sooriyakanda-ghosts-scapegoats-and-real-killers |website=dailymirror.lk |publisher=Daily Mirror |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter a three year trial into the disappearances of the students, the [[High Court of Sri Lanka|High Court]] of [[Ratnapura]], found Dayananda Lokugalapaththi and several military personal of the army camp were found guilty of numerous offences under the [[Penal Code]] and sentenced to prison terms of ten years. Since the bodies of the students were not discovered, they were not charged of murder. The third accused, Brigadier Liyanage was acquitted on the basis there was no direct evidence against him and his acquittal was not appealed by the State Prosecutor. Based on this judgment, Brigadier Liyanage appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Sri Lanka|Supreme Court]], the denial of his promotion to the rank of [[Major General]] after he was recommended by the Commander of the Army following his acquittal by the High Court. The Supreme Court found that promotion of other officers in the chain of command during the incident were promoted, it ordered that the recommendation of the Commander of the Army be carried out and compensation given. The Defence Secretary had later reported that the promotion can not be carried out due to the [[President of Sri Lanka]] in her capacity as the Commander in Chief, refused to accept the recommendation for promotion and Liyanage had already retired as a Brigadier. Liyanage's appeal to the Supreme Court on this matter resulted in the court stating that it can do no more.<ref>{{cite news |title=SC order loses potency when President says no |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/000827/news3.html |accessdate=6 August 2019 |publisher=Sunday Times |date=27 August 2000}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liyanage, Parry}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Artillery officers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan shot putters]]\n[[Category:Male shot putters]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan male athletes]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Military Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) administrators]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese military personnel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Parry Liyanage\n|birth_date=  \n|death_date=  \n|birth_place= \n|death_place=\n|placeofburial= \n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears=             \n|rank=[[Brigadier]]\n|branch= [[Sri Lanka Army]]\n|commands=Quartermaster-General,<br>Adjutant General \n|unit=[[Sri Lanka Artillery]]\n|battles=[[Sri Lankan Civil War]],<br /> [[1987-89 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|Insurrection 1987-89]]\n|awards=\n|laterwork=  \n}}\n[[Brigadier]] '''Rohan Parakrama \"Parry\" Liyanage''' was a [[Sri Lanka]]n military officer, athlete  and coach, who was the former [[Quartermaster general#Sri Lanka|Quartermaster-General]] and [[Adjutant General#Sri Lanka|Adjutant General]] of the [[Sri Lanka Army]]. He was the National record holder for [[shot put]], senior vice president of the Athletic Association of Sri Lanka and National Athletic Coach.<ref>[http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/06/16/spo06.asp Brig. Parry no more] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019105456/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/06/16/spo06.asp |date=2012-10-19 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nEducated at [[Royal College, Colombo]], he joined the army in the first batch of officers to be trained locally at the Officer Cadets\u2019 School of the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy|Army Training Center]] on 27 April 1968 and was commissioned into the [[Ceylon Artillery]] as a [[Second Lieutenant]].  \n\n== Embilipitiya Schoolboys' Affair==\nAt the height of the [[1987\u20131989 JVP insurrection]], Dayananda Lokugalapaththi, the Principal of Embilipitiya Maha Vidyalaya, got angry at several school boys for mocking the love affairs of his son with another student. Lokugalapaththi had been accused to have had the Army take the school boys to Sevana army camp where they were killed. Colonel Liyanage was the district coordination officer of the area and had been friendly with Lokugalapaththi.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hoole |first1=Rajan |title=Embilipitiya Schoolboys\u2019 Affair \u2013 The Thin End Of The Wedge |url=https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/embilipitiya-schoolboys-affair-the-thin-end-of-the-wedge/ |website=Colombo Telegraph |publisher=Colombo Telegraph |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> The boys were forced to write suicide notes prior to death, forced to eat broken glass and nails, and subsequently buried in the [[Sooriyakanda mass grave]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Akmeemana |first1=Gamini |title=Sooriyakanda: ghosts, scapegoats and real killers |url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/110628/Sooriyakanda-ghosts-scapegoats-and-real-killers |website=dailymirror.lk |publisher=Daily Mirror |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter a three year trial into the disappearances of the students, the [[High Court of Sri Lanka|High Court]] of [[Ratnapura]], found Dayananda Lokugalapaththi and several military personal of the army camp were found guilty of numerous offences under the [[Penal Code]] and sentenced to prison terms of ten years. Since the bodies of the students were not discovered, they were not charged of murder. The third accused, Brigadier Liyanage was acquitted on the basis there was no direct evidence against him and his acquittal was not appealed by the State Prosecutor. Based on this judgment, Brigadier Liyanage appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Sri Lanka|Supreme Court]], the denial of his promotion to the rank of [[Major General]] after he was recommended by the Commander of the Army following his acquittal by the High Court. The Supreme Court found that promotion of other officers in the chain of command during the incident were promoted, it ordered that the recommendation of the Commander of the Army be carried out and compensation given. The Defence Secretary had later reported that the promotion can not be carried out due to the [[President of Sri Lanka]] in her capacity as the Commander in Chief, refused to accept the recommendation for promotion and Liyanage had already retired as a Brigadier. Liyanage's appeal to the Supreme Court on this matter resulted in the court stating that it can do no more.<ref>{{cite news |title=SC order loses potency when President says no |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/000827/news3.html |accessdate=6 August 2019 |publisher=Sunday Times |date=27 August 2000}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liyanage, Parry}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Artillery officers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan shot putters]]\n[[Category:Male shot putters]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan male athletes]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Military Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) administrators]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese military personnel]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove flagicon from infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parry_Liyanage"}
